'''DFS-Kopernikus 3''' (or '''Deutscher Fernmelde Satellit-3''' and '''HellasSat 1''') was a [[communications satellite]] operated by [[Deutsche Telekom]].
== Satellite == The DFS series of satellites debuted in 1989 with the third being launched in 1992. Ordered in 1983 and produced by the GESAT consortium of [[Messerschmitt-Bölkow-Blohm|MBB]] (flight segment prime contractor), [[Siemens]] (overall prime contractor), [[ANT Nachrichtentechnik]] (payload), [[Standard Elektrik Lorenz]] (digital switching equipment), and [[Dornier Flugzeugwerke|Dornier]] Systems (ground control system), DFS spacecraft are smaller than TV-Sat: on-station mass of DFS is {{convert|850|kg|lb}} with a {{convert|15.4|m|ft}} solar array span providing up to 1.5 kilowatts of electrical power. The satellite also used a propulsion system S400.
The communications payload includes ten 14/11-12 [[GHz]] [[transponder]]s with five spares and one experimental 30/20&nbsp;GHz transponder with one spare. At the end of 1994 DFS 1-3 were stationed at 33.5 degrees east, 28.5 degrees east, and 23.5 degrees east, respectively. Like TV-Sat, the DFS Kopernikus series has been concluded.
DFS 3 was leased to the Greek company [[Hellas Sat]] in 2002 as a stop-gap measure. It was retired in 2003.
== Launch == DFS-Kopernikus 3 was launched by a [[Delta (rocket family)|Delta]] rocket from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]], [[Florida]], [[United States]], at 09:47 UTC on October 12, 1992.<ref name="nssdc">{{cite web|url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraftDisplay.do?id=1992-066A|title=DFS Kopernikus 3 |work=NSSDC Master Catalog|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref>
