{{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Monaco}} "L'amour s'en va" | image = [[Image:Françoise Hardy -L'amour s'en va.jpg|250px]] | caption = | year = 1963 | country = Monaco | artist = [[Françoise Hardy]] | as = | with = | language = French | languages = | composer = [[Françoise Hardy]] | lyricist = [[Françoise Hardy]] | conductor = [[Raymond Lefèvre]] | place = 5th | points = 25 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1963mc from Diggiloo Thrush] | prev = "Dis rien" | prev_link = Dis rien | next = "Où sont-elles passées" | next_link = Où sont-elles passées }} '''"L'amour s'en va"''' ("Love goes away") was the [[Monaco|Monegasque]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963]], composed and performed in [[French language|French]] by French singer and actress [[Françoise Hardy]].
==Background== Hardy had had her breakthrough as an 18-year-old in late 1962 with the [[yé-yé]] hit "[[Tous les garçons et les filles (song)|Tous les garçons et les filles]]", which sold some 700,000 copies in France alone,<ref>[http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php?debut=250 Bestsellers Les Meilleures Ventes Tout Temps de 45 T. / Singles, InfoDisc] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113170508/http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php?debut=250 |date=2008-11-13 }}, accessed on line April 30, 2009.</ref> and she would go on to become one of the [[francophone]] world's most successful and popular artists of the 1960s - as well as an influential [[fashion icon]].
"L'amour s'en va" is in the ''chanson'' style, popular in the early years of the Contest. Hardy sings about a relationship which is conducted in the knowledge that love is a fleeting thing - however this does not seem to matter to either of the lovers involved, as they ''"chase after it"''. Hardy also recorded the song in Italian and German, as "L'amore va" and "Die Liebe geht", respectively.
The song was performed fifteenth on the night (following Belgium's [[Jacques Raymond]] with "[[Waarom?]]" and preceding [[Luxembourg]]'s [[Nana Mouskouri]] with "[[À force de prier]]"). At the close of voting, it had received 25 points, placing 5th in a field of 16. "L'amour s'en va" however went on to win Hardy the prestigious French award [[Grand Prix du Disque]] in 1963 and some forty years after its original release the song still counts as one of her signature tunes.
It was succeeded as [[Monaco in the Eurovision Song Contest|Monegasque representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1964|1964 Contest]] by [[Romuald Figuier|Romuald]] with "[[Où sont-elles passées]]".
==Sources and external links== * [http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=280 Official Eurovision Song Contest site, history by year, 1963] * [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1963mc Detailed info and lyrics, The Diggiloo Thrush, "L'amour s'en va".] * [https://web.archive.org/web/20060614193814/http://www.rfimusique.com/siteEn/biographie/biographie_6310.asp Radio France Internationale, biography Françoise Hardy]
